defaultQ137default              defaultLindsay Roy:default Michael, can you just clarify what the essence is of this cultural change?
default&#xa0;defaultMichael Fallondefault: When I was first in government more than 20 years ago, Government regarded data as its property. There is an understanding now that that data belongs to all of us—it belongs to the public that we serve and it belongs to the taxpayers who have paid for its collection. That has been a big cultural change. 
defaultMr Hurd:default If I may add to that, Chair, there is also a change in terms of increased perception of the value of this data. 10 or 15 years ago I am not sure we understood the value of it, because there was not necessarily an information marketplace; there is now. Government is gradually waking up to the fact that we are sitting on something valuable and maybe we should share it. 
default&#xa0;
